{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:37:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.06,0,0.34,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8131"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18984"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) is a common condition affecting older men. The condition involves changes in both tissue growth and smooth muscle tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of benign prostatic hyperplasia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased apoptosis with stromal and epithelial hyperplasia","Increased apoptosis with stromal atrophy","Decreased alpha-1 receptors in prostatic tissue","Epithelial hyperplasia without stromal changes","Reduced androgen receptor expression"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn benign prostatic hyperplasia, there is \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased apoptosis with stromal and epithelial hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E. This results in enlargement of the prostate gland through both increased cell proliferation and reduced cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased apoptosis with stromal atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E - Apoptosis is actually reduced in BPH, not increased\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased alpha-1 receptors in prostatic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Alpha-1 receptors are increased in BPH, contributing to increased smooth muscle tone\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpithelial hyperplasia without stromal changes\u003C/strong\u003E - Both stromal and epithelial components are involved in BPH\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced androgen receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E - Androgen signalling remains important in BPH development\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBPH has both static and dynamic components. The static component involves tissue growth due to reduced apoptosis and increased cell proliferation. The dynamic component involves increased smooth muscle tone due to alpha-1 receptor upregulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Benign prostatic hyperplasia involves decreased apoptosis and increased proliferation of both stromal and epithelial tissue","BPH has both static (tissue growth) and dynamic (smooth muscle tone) components","Alpha-1 receptors are increased in BPH, contributing to increased smooth muscle tone"],"references":["Lee CH, Akin-Olugbade O, Kirschenbaum A. Overview of prostate anatomy, histology, and pathology. Endocrinol Metab Clin North Am. 2011 Sep;40(3):565-75, viii-ix. doi: 10.1016/j.ecl.2011.05.012. PMID: 21889721.","Madersbacher S, Sampson N, Culig Z. Pathophysiology of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia and Benign Prostatic Enlargement: A Mini-Review. Gerontology. 2019;65(5):458-464. doi: 10.1159/000496289. Epub 2019 Apr 3. PMID: 30943489.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15089"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:41:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:43:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7777"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67915"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data